body:
I was able to get libuv working in a Visual Studio project and I wrote up an article, [_Using libuv with Windows and Visual Studio: Getting Started_](http://ericeastwood.com/blog/24/using-libuv-with-windows-and-visual-studio-getting-started), explaining how I got it all set up and working.

I am now wanting to build with [node-gyp](https://www.npmjs.com/package/node-gyp) but I am running into some issues.

I am getting syntax errors when building with node-gyp like `..\..\uv\src\win\tty.c(173): error C2146: syntax error : missing ')' before identifier 'mode'`

_[Full verbose build output pastebin](http://pastebin.com/wyXT0wRQ): `node ../node_modules/node-gyp/bin/node-gyp.js build --verbose`_

I am using the latest code from the v1.x branch. I also tried the [1.4.2 release on libuv.org](http://libuv.org/dist/v1.4.2/). I have also tried with and without running vcbuild.bat.

What do I need to do to get a successful build?

I checked the [io.js source](https://github.com/iojs/io.js/blob/5094a0fde3c3e8925f6f9cb7ff0e65e527a4845e/node.gyp), etc to try to find what they are doing but nothing jumped out at me.

---
### `binding.gyp`

```
{
    "targets": [
        {
            'target_name': 'test',
            'type': 'executable',
            'sources': [
                'main.cpp'
            ],
            "dependencies": [
                "uv/uv.gyp:libuv"
            ]
        }
    ]
}
```
### `main.cpp`

```
#pragma comment (lib, "libuv.lib")
#pragma comment (lib, "ws2_32.lib")
#pragma comment (lib, "psapi.lib")
#pragma comment (lib, "Iphlpapi.lib")


#include <iostream>
//#include <stdio.h>
#include <string.h>
//#include <unistd.h>
//#include <io.h>
#include <uv.h>

#include <regex>


std::string stripAnsiEscapeCodes(std::string input) {
    // from: https://github.com/sindresorhus/ansi-regex/blob/47fb974630af70998157b30fad6eb5e5bd7c7cd6/index.js
    std::regex reg("(?:(?:\033\\[)|\233)(?:(?:[0-9]{1,3})?(?:(?:;[0-9]{0,3})*)?[A-M|f-m])|\033[A-M]");
    std::string output = std::regex_replace(input, reg, "");

    return output;
}

void ccout(std::string message, uv_write_t* req, uv_stream_t* handle) {
    // If the terminal doesn't support ANSI, strip it for clarity
    if (uv_guess_handle(1) != UV_TTY) {
        message = stripAnsiEscapeCodes(message);
    }

    uv_buf_t buf;
    buf.base = (char*)message.c_str();
    buf.len = strlen(buf.base);
    uv_write(req, handle, &buf, 1, NULL);
};



uv_loop_t *loop;
uv_tty_t tty;
int main() {
    loop = uv_default_loop();

    uv_tty_init(loop, &tty, 1, 0);
    uv_tty_set_mode(&tty, UV_TTY_MODE_NORMAL);

    ccout("\033[41;37mHello TTY\n\033[0m", &uv_write_t(), (uv_stream_t*)&tty);
    ccout("asdf\n", &uv_write_t(), (uv_stream_t*)&tty);
    ccout("qwer\n", &uv_write_t(), (uv_stream_t*)&tty);

    // To be called when the program exits. Resets TTY settings to default values for the next process to take over.
    uv_tty_reset_mode();
    return uv_run(loop, UV_RUN_DEFAULT);

    return 0;
}
```
